Here are both approaches:

**1. Passing a simple string (product ID):**

```csharp
// From ProductListPage or its ViewModel
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
```

**2. Passing a full object:**

```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }   // complex object → must use this overload
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
```

**Receiving both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1 – simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service, etc.
            LoadProduct(productId);
        }

        // Approach 2 – full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var prodObj) && prodObj is Product product)
        {
            // use directly — no deserialization needed
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }
}
```

**Wire the ViewModel to the page:**

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | Query-string syntax `?key=val` | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Received as** | `object` (string at runtime) | Original CLR type — cast it |
| **Survives URI serialization** | Yes | No — don't mix into the URI |

**Tip:** Register the route in `AppShell` or via `Routing.RegisterRoute`:

```csharp
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

Both approaches land in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support either (or both) in one ViewModel.
